  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering:\n\n1. United States Approach\n- Comprehensive Bank Secrecy Act\n- Strict reporting requirements\n- Aggressive criminal prosecution\n- Significant financial penalties\n- Focus on international financial transactions\n\n2. European Union Approach\n- Unified Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Centralized regulatory framework\n- Emphasis on financial institution compliance\n- Strong cross-border cooperation\n- Proportional criminal/civil sanctions\n\n3. United Kingdom Model\n- Advanced technological monitoring\n- Risk-based regulatory supervision\n- Extensive financial intelligence capabilities\n- Collaborative public-private enforcement\n- Sophisticated asset recovery mechanisms\n\n4. Swiss Model\n- Traditional banking secrecy laws\n- Complex identification requirements\n- Gradual internationalization of standards\n- Sophisticated due diligence protocols\n\n5. Asian Approaches\n- Varied regulatory environments\n- China: Strict state control\n- Singapore: Highly transparent system\n- Japan: Rigorous compliance frameworks\n\n6. Common Characteristics\n- Customer identification requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International information sharing\n- Risk-based compliance strategies\n\nThese approaches demonstrate significant legal diversity while converging around core anti-money laundering principles.",
